[## [SECTION: Step 1 — Understand the GitOps Architecture]]


14
03:33:42,000 --> 03:33:48,000
Before we write any files, let me explain the GitOps architecture.

15
03:33:48,000 --> 03:33:54,000
A developer pushes code to GitHub.
ArgoCD detects the diff.

16
03:33:54,000 --> 03:34:00,000
It polls every 3 minutes, or you can configure a webhook.
The diff shows what changed in the Git repo.

17
03:34:00,000 --> 03:34:06,000
The ApplicationSet generates one Application per environment.
Dev, staging, and prod each get their own.

18
03:34:06,000 --> 03:34:12,000
Each environment has a different sync policy.
Dev auto-syncs immediately. Changes apply as soon as they're pushed.

19
03:34:12,000 --> 03:34:18,000
Staging also auto-syncs immediately.
For testing before production.

20
03:34:18,000 --> 03:34:24,000
Production requires manual sync only.
And only allowed during a specific window, 2 AM to 6 AM UTC.

21
03:34:24,000 --> 03:34:30,000
ArgoCD renders Helm templates with environment-specific values.
It then runs kubectl apply using server-side apply.

22
03:34:30,000 --> 03:34:36,000
Finally, it sends a Slack notification.
Sync succeeded or failed.

23
03:34:36,000 --> 03:34:42,000
Why GitOps? Without it, deployments happen via helm upgrade.
From someone's laptop or a CI runner.

24
03:34:42,000 --> 03:34:48,000
The cluster state is not reproducible from Git alone.
If the cluster is destroyed, you don't know exactly what was running.

25
03:34:48,000 --> 03:34:54,000
With ArgoCD, the cluster continuously reconciles toward the Git state.
The Git repository IS the source of truth.

26
03:34:54,000 --> 03:35:00,000
Let me summarize the GitOps flow.

27
03:35:00,000 --> 03:35:06,000
Git push triggers ArgoCD diff.
ApplicationSet creates environment Applications.

28
03:35:06,000 --> 03:35:12,000
Dev auto-syncs, staging auto-syncs, prod manual sync only.
Helm renders templates, kubectl applies, Slack notifies.

29
03:35:12,000 --> 03:35:18,000
The cluster always matches what's in Git.
This is the foundation of production-grade Kubernetes.


[## [SECTION: Step 2 — Install Cilium (Component #101)]]


30
03:35:18,000 --> 03:35:24,000
Now let's install Cilium for eBPF networking.
Cilium must be installed before ArgoCD.

31
03:35:24,000 --> 03:35:30,000
Why before? ArgoCD pods need networking to start.
You need the network to sync the network.

32
03:35:30,000 --> 03:35:36,000
First, add the Cilium Helm repository and update it.
Then install Cilium with specific settings.

33
03:35:36,000 --> 03:35:42,000
The most important setting is kubeProxyReplacement equals true.
This replaces kube-proxy entirely with Cilium's eBPF datapath.

34
03:35:42,000 --> 03:35:48,000
kube-proxy traditionally uses iptables for load balancing.
Every packet goes through a chain of rules in userspace.

35
03:35:48,000 --> 03:35:54,000
Cilium's eBPF datapath runs in the Linux kernel.
It is much faster and more efficient.

36
03:35:54,000 --> 03:36:00,000
We also enable Hubble relay and UI.
Hubble is Cilium's observability layer.

37
03:36:00,000 --> 03:36:06,000
Hubble metrics include DNS, drops, TCP flows, and HTTP.
It captures source and destination namespaces, workloads, and traffic direction.

38
03:36:06,000 --> 03:36:12,000
Hubble UI gives you a graphical view of network flows.
You can see which services are talking to which.

39
03:36:12,000 --> 03:36:18,000
On EKS, we use ipam.mode equals eni.
ENI stands for Elastic Network Interface.

40
03:36:18,000 --> 03:36:24,000
Cilium manages pod IPs directly on the EC2 ENI.
No overlay network, native VPC routing.

41
03:36:24,000 --> 03:36:30,000
The EKS API endpoint is required for kube-proxy replacement.
Cilium needs to know where the Kubernetes API server is.

42
03:36:30,000 --> 03:36:36,000
Our Cilium installation is complete.
Now let's verify it.


[## [SECTION: Step 3 — Verify Cilium (Component #102)]]


43
03:36:36,000 --> 03:36:42,000
Now let's verify that Cilium is working correctly.

44
03:36:42,000 --> 03:36:48,000
First, check that all Cilium agents are running.
kubectl get pods in kube-system with the Cilium label.

45
03:36:48,000 --> 03:36:54,000
All pods should be in Running state.
If any are pending or crash looping, check your installation.

46
03:36:54,000 --> 03:37:00,000
Next, run the connectivity test.
cilium connectivity test.

47
03:37:00,000 --> 03:37:06,000
This deploys test pods and verifies L3, L4, and L7 networking.
It checks if pods can reach each other correctly.

48
03:37:06,000 --> 03:37:12,000
If the test passes, Cilium is working.
If it fails, something is wrong with your configuration.

49
03:37:12,000 --> 03:37:18,000
Use the Hubble CLI to observe live network flows.
hubble observe with dash dash namespace and dash dash follow.

50
03:37:18,000 --> 03:37:24,000
This shows every packet flowing through your cluster.
You can filter by namespace, verdict, or protocol.

51
03:37:24,000 --> 03:37:30,000
Finally, launch the Hubble UI in your browser.
cilium hubble ui.

52
03:37:30,000 --> 03:37:36,000
Our Cilium verification is complete.
Cilium is ready for zero-trust policies.


[## [SECTION: Step 4 — Deny-All Network Policy (Component #104)]]


53
03:37:36,000 --> 03:37:42,000
Now let's apply the baseline deny-all network policy.
This is Component 104.

54
03:37:42,000 --> 03:37:48,000
The policy is called default-deny-all.
It matches all pods in the financial-rag namespace.

55
03:37:48,000 --> 03:37:54,000
Ingress is empty, meaning deny all incoming traffic.
No pod can receive traffic from any source.

56
03:37:54,000 --> 03:38:00,000
Egress has one exception. DNS.
Pods need to resolve service names.

57
03:38:00,000 --> 03:38:06,000
Why allow DNS in the deny-all?
Without DNS, pods cannot resolve service names.

58
03:38:06,000 --> 03:38:12,000
For example, financial-rag-agent-pgvector dot svc dot cluster dot local.
That domain name needs to be resolved.

59
03:38:12,000 --> 03:38:18,000
DNS is the one egress that must be permitted.
Before any other allow rules are applied.

60
03:38:18,000 --> 03:38:24,000
The policy targets kube-dns in the kube-system namespace.
UDP port 53 and TCP port 53.

61
03:38:24,000 --> 03:38:30,000
Apply the policy with kubectl apply dash f.
Then verify with Hubble.

62
03:38:30,000 --> 03:38:36,000
hubble observe with dash dash namespace financial-rag.
And dash dash verdict DROPPED.

63
03:38:36,000 --> 03:38:42,000
You should see dropped traffic.
Everything except DNS is now blocked.

64
03:38:42,000 --> 03:38:48,000
Start with default-deny-all. No traffic flows.
Then add specific allow rules for what you need.

65
03:38:48,000 --> 03:38:54,000
This is zero-trust networking.
Deny everything by default, explicitly permit what's necessary.

66
03:38:54,000 --> 03:39:00,000
DNS is the only exception in the baseline.
Pods cannot function without name resolution.

67
03:39:00,000 --> 03:39:06,000
Our deny-all policy is complete.
Zero-trust networking is now active.


[## [SECTION: Step 5 — L7 HTTP Policies (Components #105–107)]]


68
03:39:06,000 --> 03:39:12,000
Now let's add L7 HTTP policies with Cilium.

69
03:39:12,000 --> 03:39:18,000
Let me explain what L7 enforcement means in practice.
This is critical.

70
03:39:18,000 --> 03:39:24,000
Without L7 policy, if someone sends a DELETE request to your API.
The request reaches your FastAPI application.

71
03:39:24,000 --> 03:39:30,000
FastAPI returns a 405 Method Not Allowed.
But the request still consumed resources. It reached your app.

72
03:39:30,000 --> 03:39:36,000
With L7 policy, that DELETE request is dropped at the kernel level.
It never reaches your application at all.

73
03:39:36,000 --> 03:39:42,000
Even if FastAPI had a bug that incorrectly handled DELETE on the wrong route.
The kernel already dropped the packet. The bug never triggers.

74
03:39:42,000 --> 03:39:48,000
This is defense in depth. The network layer protects your application.
Even if your application code has vulnerabilities.

75
03:39:48,000 --> 03:39:54,000
The API L7 policy allows only specific methods and paths.

76
03:39:54,000 --> 03:40:00,000
From the outside world, the ALB can send GET requests to slash health.
And POST requests to slash query.

77
03:40:00,000 --> 03:40:06,000
From the monitoring namespace, Prometheus can send GET requests to slash metrics.
Everything else is dropped.

78
03:40:06,000 --> 03:40:12,000
No DELETE. No PUT. No docs endpoint in production.
This matches what we did in server.py with docs disabled.

79
03:40:12,000 --> 03:40:18,000
The agent L7 policy allows POST requests to slash infer from the API.
And GET slash health from monitoring.

80
03:40:18,000 --> 03:40:24,000
All other requests to the agent are dropped at the kernel level.
Our L7 policies are complete.


[## [SECTION: Step 6 — Istio Service Mesh]]


81
03:40:24,000 --> 03:40:30,000
Now let's add Istio for service mesh.
Istio works alongside Cilium. They do different things.

82
03:40:30,000 --> 03:40:36,000
Cilium enforces which pods can talk to which pods.
And which HTTP methods and paths are allowed.

83
03:40:36,000 --> 03:40:42,000
Istio encrypts all pod-to-pod traffic with mTLS.
And enforces service identity.

84
03:40:42,000 --> 03:40:48,000
Think of it this way.
Cilium is the bouncer at the door. It checks your ID.

85
03:40:48,000 --> 03:40:54,000
Istio is the encrypted tunnel. No one can eavesdrop on your conversation.
Even if they sneak past the bouncer.

86
03:40:54,000 --> 03:41:00,000
Install Istio using Helm charts.
First, add the repo and create the istio-system namespace.

87
03:41:00,000 --> 03:41:06,000
Install the base CRDs, then the control plane called istiod.
Then enable sidecar injection for the financial-rag namespace.

88
03:41:06,000 --> 03:41:12,000
PeerAuthentication enables strict mTLS.
mTLS stands for mutual Transport Layer Security.

89
03:41:12,000 --> 03:41:18,000
Both sides of the connection present certificates.
The client proves its identity to the server.

90
03:41:18,000 --> 03:41:24,000
The server proves its identity to the client.
No one can impersonate either side.

91
03:41:24,000 --> 03:41:30,000
mode STRICT means reject any plaintext traffic.
All communication must be encrypted.

92
03:41:30,000 --> 03:41:36,000
Istio AuthorizationPolicy works on service identities.
Not on IP addresses or pod labels.

93
03:41:36,000 --> 03:41:42,000
The deny-all policy has an empty spec. That means deny everything.
No traffic is allowed in the namespace.

94
03:41:42,000 --> 03:41:48,000
Then we add specific allow rules.
allow-gateway-to-api allows only the Istio ingress gateway.

95
03:41:48,000 --> 03:41:54,000
The principal is a service account.
cluster.local slash ns slash istio-system slash sa slash istio-ingressgateway.

96
03:41:54,000 --> 03:42:00,000
Only that exact service account can call the API.
No other pod can.

97
03:42:00,000 --> 03:42:06,000
DestinationRules control how traffic flows to a service.
Connection pool limits prevent a single pod from being overwhelmed.

98
03:42:06,000 --> 03:42:12,000
Outlier detection is a circuit breaker.
If a pod starts returning errors, Istio ejects it.

99
03:42:12,000 --> 03:42:18,000
For 30 seconds, no traffic goes to that pod.
Then it's re-evaluated.

100
03:42:18,000 --> 03:42:24,000
Load balancing uses LEAST_REQUEST.
Send traffic to the pod with the fewest active requests.

101
03:42:24,000 --> 03:42:30,000
The Gateway defines TLS termination at the mesh edge.
It listens on port 443 for HTTPS traffic.

102
03:42:30,000 --> 03:42:36,000
Our Istio configuration is complete.
The cluster now has mTLS and service identity.


[## [SECTION: Step 7 — Install ArgoCD (Components #108–110)]]


103
03:42:36,000 --> 03:42:42,000
Now let's install ArgoCD for GitOps.
We'll use a bootstrap script that automates everything.

104
03:42:42,000 --> 03:42:48,000
First, it adds the ArgoCD Helm repository and updates it.

105
03:42:48,000 --> 03:42:54,000
The script requires environment variables.
CLUSTER_NAME, ARGOCD_VERSION, and ENV.

106
03:42:54,000 --> 03:43:00,000
It also requires GITHUB_TOKEN for repository access.
And optional SLACK_TOKEN and PAGERDUTY_PROD_KEY for notifications.

107
03:43:00,000 --> 03:43:06,000
The script creates the argocd namespace.
It disables Istio injection for ArgoCD components.

108
03:43:06,000 --> 03:43:12,000
Then it installs ArgoCD using the Helm chart.
With wait and timeout 10 minutes.

109
03:43:12,000 --> 03:43:18,000
After installation, it retrieves the initial admin password.
The password is stored in a Kubernetes secret.

110
03:43:18,000 --> 03:43:24,000
It starts a port-forward to access the ArgoCD server.
Then logs in with the admin credentials.

111
03:43:24,000 --> 03:43:30,000
The script adds your Git repository to ArgoCD.
It uses the GITHUB_TOKEN for authentication.

112
03:43:30,000 --> 03:43:36,000
This allows ArgoCD to pull manifests directly from Git.
No manual kubectl apply needed.

113
03:43:36,000 --> 03:43:42,000
Next, it applies RBAC configuration.
This controls who can do what in ArgoCD.

114
03:43:42,000 --> 03:43:48,000
The policy.csv file defines roles and permissions.
It's patched into the argocd-rbac-cm ConfigMap.

115
03:43:48,000 --> 03:43:54,000
If SLACK_TOKEN is provided, it creates a secret.
This enables Slack notifications for sync events.

116
03:43:54,000 --> 03:44:00,000
You get notified when a deployment succeeds or fails.
No need to watch the ArgoCD UI constantly.

117
03:44:00,000 --> 03:44:06,000
Finally, it applies three ApplicationSets.
infra-appset, env-appset, and apps-appset.

118
03:44:06,000 --> 03:44:12,000
The App of Apps pattern.
One root ApplicationSet manages all other applications.

119
03:44:12,000 --> 03:44:18,000
Let me explain the bootstrap order.

120
03:44:18,000 --> 03:44:24,000
First, apply infra-appset. This deploys infrastructure components.
Namespace operators, service monitors, and cluster add-ons.

121
03:44:24,000 --> 03:44:30,000
Then env-appset deploys environment-specific configurations.
One Application per environment. Dev, staging, prod.

122
03:44:30,000 --> 03:44:36,000
Finally, apps-appset deploys the application itself.
The API, agent, ingestion CronJob, and databases.

123
03:44:36,000 --> 03:44:42,000
Our ArgoCD installation is complete.
Now let's look at the ArgoCD Project.


[## [SECTION: Step 8 — ArgoCD Project (RBAC + Sync Windows)]]


124
03:44:42,000 --> 03:44:48,000
Now let's create the ArgoCD Project.

125
03:44:48,000 --> 03:44:54,000
Think of an ArgoCD Project like a gated community.
It has rules about who can come in and what they can do.

126
03:44:54,000 --> 03:45:00,000
First, sourceRepos lists where you can get your blueprints from.
Your GitHub repo, and Helm repos like Cilium and Istio.

127
03:45:00,000 --> 03:45:06,000
No one can deploy from outside these sources.
This prevents someone from using a fake, malicious chart.

128
03:45:06,000 --> 03:45:12,000
Next, destinations lists which namespaces you can deploy to.
financial-rag, istio-system, karpenter, monitoring, and others.

129
03:45:12,000 --> 03:45:18,000
You cannot deploy to a random namespace.
Every deployment must go to an approved destination.

130
03:45:18,000 --> 03:45:24,000
clusterResourceWhitelist lists cluster-level resources you can create.
Namespaces, ClusterRoles, CustomResourceDefinitions.

131
03:45:24,000 --> 03:45:30,000
Without this, you couldn't create a namespace.
But you also cannot delete or modify critical cluster resources.

132
03:45:30,000 --> 03:45:36,000
Now syncWindows. This is like a schedule.
It says when you ARE allowed to deploy and when you ARE NOT.

133
03:45:36,000 --> 03:45:42,000
Dev and staging have a 24-hour allow window. They can deploy anytime.
Manual sync is allowed but auto-sync is also enabled.

134
03:45:42,000 --> 03:45:48,000
Production has a 4-hour allow window from 2 AM to 6 AM UTC.
Outside that, from 8 AM to 6 PM on weekdays, deployments are DENIED.

135
03:45:48,000 --> 03:45:54,000
This prevents accidental production changes during business hours.
Even if you hit sync, ArgoCD blocks it.

136
03:45:54,000 --> 03:46:00,000
Now RBAC roles. This controls who can do what.

137
03:46:00,000 --> 03:46:06,000
The platform-engineer role can sync anything in any environment.
They are the only ones who can touch production.

138
03:46:06,000 --> 03:46:12,000
The developer role can only sync dev and staging.
They can look at production but cannot change it.

139
03:46:12,000 --> 03:46:18,000
The ci-bot role is for your CI pipeline.
It has full sync permissions but can't approve manual promotions.

140
03:46:18,000 --> 03:46:24,000
Now the ApplicationSet. This creates one Application per environment.
Dev, staging, and prod.

141
03:46:24,000 --> 03:46:30,000
The rolling sync strategy controls promotion order.
First dev, then staging, then prod.

142
03:46:30,000 --> 03:46:36,000
If dev fails to sync, the pipeline stops.
It won't try staging or prod.

143
03:46:36,000 --> 03:46:42,000
The list generator defines each environment's settings.
Dev uses values.yaml, auto-sync enabled, image tag latest.

144
03:46:42,000 --> 03:46:48,000
Staging uses the same values.yaml. Also auto-sync.
Also image tag latest.

145
03:46:48,000 --> 03:46:54,000
Production uses values.prod.yaml. Auto-sync is false.
Image tag is pinned to 1.0.0, not latest.

146
03:46:54,000 --> 03:47:00,000
The template defines what the Application looks like.
It pulls from your Helm chart.

147
03:47:00,000 --> 03:47:06,000
The sync policy has retries. 5 attempts with exponential backoff.
If it fails, it waits 30 seconds, then 60, then 2 minutes, then 4.

148
03:47:06,000 --> 03:47:12,000
ignoreDifferences tells ArgoCD to ignore certain fields.
Here it ignores spec.replicas in Deployments.

149
03:47:12,000 --> 03:47:18,000
Why? Because the HorizontalPodAutoscaler changes replica counts.
ArgoCD would otherwise try to revert them.

150
03:47:18,000 --> 03:47:24,000
Our ArgoCD Project and ApplicationSet are complete.
Now let's promote to production.


[## [SECTION: Step 9 — Promote to Production]]


151
03:47:24,000 --> 03:47:30,000
Now let's promote to production.
First, see what's out of sync.

152
03:47:30,000 --> 03:47:36,000
argocd app diff financial-rag-prod.
This shows the difference between Git and the cluster.

153
03:47:36,000 --> 03:47:42,000
Then sync manually with argocd app sync dash dash prune.
This brings the cluster into alignment with Git.

154
03:47:42,000 --> 03:47:48,000
Wait for the rollout with argocd app wait dash dash health.
This blocks until everything is healthy.

155
03:47:48,000 --> 03:47:54,000
If something goes wrong, roll back with argocd app rollback.
Followed by the revision number.

156
03:47:54,000 --> 03:48:00,000
Rollback to revision 1 reverts to the previous known-good state.
No manual fix needed.

157
03:48:00,000 --> 03:48:06,000
Let me summarize the GitOps promotion flow.

158
03:48:06,000 --> 03:48:12,000
Developer pushes to GitHub. ArgoCD sees the change.
Dev auto-syncs. Staging auto-syncs.

159
03:48:12,000 --> 03:48:18,000
Platform engineer manually syncs production within the allowed window.
If something breaks, roll back to previous revision.

160
03:48:18,000 --> 03:48:24,000
Git is the source of truth.
The cluster always tries to match what's in Git.


[## [SECTION: Step 10 — Cilium ServiceMonitor (Component #118)]]


161
03:48:24,000 --> 03:48:30,000
Now let's add the Cilium ServiceMonitor.
This tells Prometheus to scrape metrics from Cilium.

162
03:48:30,000 --> 03:48:36,000
Cilium and Hubble produce important metrics.
Network flows, dropped packets, DNS requests, and HTTP traffic.

163
03:48:36,000 --> 03:48:42,000
We want these metrics in Prometheus.
So we can see them in Grafana dashboards.

164
03:48:42,000 --> 03:48:48,000
The first ServiceMonitor is for the Cilium agent.
It targets pods with the label app.kubernetes.io/name equals hubble.

165
03:48:48,000 --> 03:48:54,000
It scrapes the hubble-metrics port on path slash metrics.
Every 30 seconds.

166
03:48:54,000 --> 03:49:00,000
It adds a relabeling. It copies the node name into a label called node.
So you can see metrics per Kubernetes node.

167
03:49:00,000 --> 03:49:06,000
The second ServiceMonitor is for the Cilium operator.
It targets pods with the label io.cilium/app equals operator.

168
03:49:06,000 --> 03:49:12,000
It scrapes the prometheus port on path slash metrics.
Also every 30 seconds.

169
03:49:12,000 --> 03:49:18,000
Apply the ServiceMonitor with kubectl apply dash f.
It goes in the monitoring namespace.

170
03:49:18,000 --> 03:49:24,000
After applying, check that metrics are flowing.
You can port-forward to Prometheus and query for cilium_ prefix.

171
03:49:24,000 --> 03:49:30,000
Or check the targets page in the Prometheus UI.
The Cilium targets should be UP.

172
03:49:30,000 --> 03:49:36,000
Our Cilium ServiceMonitor is complete.
Cilium metrics are now scraped by Prometheus.


[## [SECTION: Phase 9 Verification]]


173
03:49:36,000 --> 03:49:42,000
Now let's verify everything works.

174
03:49:42,000 --> 03:49:48,000
First, check that all Cilium agents are healthy.
kubectl get pods in kube-system with the Cilium label.

175
03:49:48,000 --> 03:49:54,000
All pods should be Running.
No crash loops, no pending.

176
03:49:54,000 --> 03:50:00,000
Run the Cilium connectivity test.
cilium connectivity test with dash dash test-namespace financial-rag.

177
03:50:00,000 --> 03:50:06,000
This deploys test pods and verifies L3, L4, and L7 policies.
Everything should pass.

178
03:50:06,000 --> 03:50:12,000
Next, check ArgoCD.
argocd app list.

179
03:50:12,000 --> 03:50:18,000
Dev and staging should be Synced.
Production may be OutOfSync until you manually approve.

180
03:50:18,000 --> 03:50:24,000
Now check Hubble for unexpected drops.
hubble observe with dash dash namespace financial-rag.

181
03:50:24,000 --> 03:50:30,000
Add dash dash verdict DROPPED and dash dash last 100.
You should see very few dropped packets.

182
03:50:30,000 --> 03:50:36,000
DNS is allowed. Health checks are allowed.
Everything else should be either allowed or correctly blocked.

183
03:50:36,000 --> 03:50:42,000
Finally, verify Istio mTLS.
istioctl x describe service financial-rag-agent-api.financial-rag.

184
03:50:42,000 --> 03:50:48,000
This shows the service details.
It should confirm that STRICT mTLS is enabled.

185
03:50:48,000 --> 03:50:54,000
Let me summarize Phase 9.

186
03:50:54,000 --> 03:51:00,000
We installed Cilium with eBPF networking.
kubeProxyReplacement true replaced kube-proxy.

187
03:51:00,000 --> 03:51:06,000
We applied a default-deny-all network policy.
Only DNS was allowed out.

188
03:51:06,000 --> 03:51:12,000
Then we added L7 HTTP policies.
Only specific methods and paths are allowed to the API.

189
03:51:12,000 --> 03:51:18,000
We installed Istio for service mesh.
PeerAuthentication with STRICT mTLS encrypts all traffic.

190
03:51:18,000 --> 03:51:24,000
AuthorizationPolicy denies everything by default.
Then allows specific service accounts.

191
03:51:24,000 --> 03:51:30,000
DestinationRules control connection pools and circuit breakers.
Outlier detection ejects failing pods.

192
03:51:30,000 --> 03:51:36,000
We installed ArgoCD for GitOps.
The bootstrap script automated the entire setup.

193
03:51:36,000 --> 03:51:42,000
The AppProject defines which repos, namespaces, and resources are allowed.
SyncWindows block production deployments during business hours.

194
03:51:42,000 --> 03:51:48,000
The ApplicationSet creates one Application per environment.
Dev and staging auto-sync. Production requires manual approval.

195
03:51:48,000 --> 03:51:54,000
We added Cilium ServiceMonitors for Prometheus.
Now we have full network observability.

196
03:51:54,000 --> 03:52:00,000
Phase 9 is complete.
The Financial RAG Agent now runs on a zero-trust, GitOps-managed Kubernetes cluster.

197
03:52:00,000 --> 03:52:06,000
This is production-grade infrastructure.
Every change is reviewed, approved, and audited through Git.

